Input-Output¶

The mfm.io module contains all classes, functions and modules relevant for file input and outputs. In particular three kinds of file-types are handled:

  1. Comma-separated files mfm.io.ascii

  2. PDB-file mfm.io.pdb

  3. TTTR-files containing photon data mfm.io.photons

  4. XYZ-files containing coordinates mfm.io.xyz

  5. DX-files containing densities mfm.io.dx

  6. SDT-files containing time-resolved fluorescence decays mfm.io.sdtfile

CSV-Files¶

PDB-Files¶

TTTR-Files¶

Read TTTR files.

TTTR files contain time-tagged-time-resolved records typically recorded in single-molecule experiments and on confocal laser scanning setups.

Author

Thomas-Otavio Peulen

class mfm.io.photons.Photons(p_object, reading_routine=None, **kwargs)[source]¶
Parameters

  • p_object – Is either a list of filenames or a single string containing the path to one file. If the first argument is n

  • reading_routine (Optional[str]) – The file type of the files passed using the first argument (p_object) is specified using the ‘file_type’ parameter. This string is either ‘hdf’ or ‘bh132’, ‘bh630_x48’, ‘ht3’, ‘iss’. If the file type is not an hdf file the files are temporarily converted to hdf-files to guarantee a consistent interface.

  • kwargs –

Returns

Examples

>>> import glob
>>> import mfm.io
>>> directory = './test/data/tttr/BH/'
>>> spc_files = glob.glob(directory+'/BH_SPC132.spc')
>>> photons = mfm.io.photons.Photons(spc_files, file_type="bh132")
>>> print(photons)

        ./test/data/tttr/spc132/hGBP1_18D\m003.spc

>>> print(photons[:10])

mfm.io.photons.read_burst_ids(filenames: 'List[str]', stack_files: 'bool' = True) → 'np.array'[source]¶

Reads Seidel-BID files and returns a list of numpy arrays. Each numpy array contains the indexes of the photons of the burst. These indexes can be used to slice a photon-stream.

Seidel BID-files only contain the first and the last photon of the Burst and not all photons of the burst. Thus, the Seidel BID-files have to be converted to array-type objects containing all photons of the burst to be able to use standard Python slicing syntax to select photons.

Parameters

  • filenames (List[str]) – filename pointing to a Seidel BID-file

  • stack_files (bool) – bool If stack is True the returned list is stacked and the numbering of the bursts is made continuous. This is the default behavior.

Return type

<built-in function array>

Returns

Examples

>>> import mfm, glob
>>> directory = "./test/data/tttr/spc132/hGBP1_18D/burstwise_All 0.1200#30\BID"
>>> files = glob.glob(directory+'/*.bst')
>>> bids = mfm.io.photons.read_burst_ids(files)
>>> bids[1]
